{
  "text": "The opiate agonists and antagonists have been shown to alter fetal behavior. At term, U50,488 stimulated fetal motor activity [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , as did U69,593 [CITATION_3] , although morphine and DAMGO had no effect on it [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Neither 3-funaltrexamine nor nor-binaltorphimine alone altered it, but the K antagonist did block the hyperactivity induced by U50,488 or by SKF-38393, indicating an interaction between the opiate and dopamine systems [CITATION_6] . Morphine [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , DAMGO [CITATION_9] , and U69,593 (476) attenuated facial wiping in response to cutaneous stimuli. The reduction of wiping by DAMGO was reversed by CTOP, and that by U69,593 was inhibited by nor-binaltorphimine [CITATION_10] , indicating that both the u and K receptors might mediate the response. Neither antagonist alone (476) nor naloxone alone [CITATION_11] , however, had any effect on facial wiping, so that there appeared to be little involvement of the endogenous opiates in this behavior.",
